         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25, WILTON PLACE, S.W. ¶ London ¶ Oct. 19 1867 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ I was exceedingly sorry to learn by your last letters (received since last mail) from Queen's Cliff ¶  that you had felt so unwell — I...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">67.10.19</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M4, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE, S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">London</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Oct. 19 1867</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was exceedingly sorry to learn by your last letters (received since last mail) from Queen's Cliff<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M to G. Bentham, 27 July 1867 and M to G. Bentham, 26 August 1867.</p>
               </note> that you had felt so unwell — I sincerely trust however that this mail may bring better accounts and that the short rest you have taken may have restored you completely</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have been going through <name key="Stylidieae">Stylidieae</name> with as much care as I could and have reduced the species to 82 of Stylidium 7 of <name key="Levenhookia">Levenhookia</name> and 1 <name key="Forstera">Forstera</name> total 90 — and there are several more that run so much into each other that one is very much puzzled to know what to do with them — Several of Brown's have been misunderstood and some rather unaccountably so.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>R. Brown (1810), pp. 565-73.</p>
               </note> Labillardière's pilosum very well described and figured is Sonders plantagineum whilst pilosum of most authors is Brown's reduplicatum. Brown's adnatum figures in the Bot Mag and Bot Reg both as adnatum and as fasciculatum though in the latter case it is expressly observed in the description that it has not what Brown gives as the essential characters of fasciculatum<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">S. adnatum</seg>: Sims (1801-26), vol. 52, t. 5298; S. Edwards (1815-28), vol. 11, t. 914. </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">S. fasciculatum</seg>: W.Hooker (1827-64), vol. 67, t. 3816; Lindley (1829-47), vol. 17, t. 1459.</p>
               </note> — and so with some others I am now at <name key="Lobelia">Lobelia</name> and regret much that Presl's bad genera should have been admitted by A. DC. without verification <name key="Pratia">Pratia</name> I suppose we must keep up though some species cannot be distinguished from corresponding ones of <name key="Lobelia">Lobelia</name> without the fruit <name key="Grammatotheca">Grammatotheca</name> is founded on characters which as far as I can discover are purely imaginary and many others are very bad.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was very sorry to see that in one of your parcels of <name key="Lobelia">Lobelia</name> a little mould had got in apparently from one of the specimens last put in perhaps not quite dry — since they have been here they have never been out of the room I work in on the second floor with a hot sun in summer and always a good fire in winter — there is nothing hurt of any consequence and I have put the specimens into fresh paper — I only mention it that you may not be alarmed if you see slight traces of it when you open the parcels — I shall send a box back as soon as I have enough ready to fill it. I have had another interruption from a week's absence from town but expect now to go on daily and steadily till the summer.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I found no specimen amongst yours of your <name key="Stylidium%20crossocephalum">Stylidium crossocephalum</name>,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham (1863-78), vol. 4, p. 8, cited M's description (B67.08.01, p. 5).</p>
               </note> I recognised at once your S. Barleei under your ms name of S. odontophyllum<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS not found.</p>
               </note> but I cannot find either amongst yours or in our more complete set of Drummonds plants anything answering to S. crossocephalum — I suppose it must be allied to S. junceum which has more or less scarious-bordered bracts and calyx lobes but never anything like the size etc. you describe — I suppose our specimens must have got astray amongst miscellanies of some other order but I should like much to see yours</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>If your government get over their financial dead lock I should feel very much obliged if you could get the order passed for my £100 so as to receive it in the course of next summer when I hope to get the volume out — as I have always to pay Reeve &amp; Co immediately on publication</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I trust you have received the 3d part of our Genera<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> which Hooker sent to you last month</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>With sincere wish that you may be quite restored to health and long enjoy it believe me</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever yours sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dr F. Mueller</p>
